New York City Shootings Data Analysis

2024-09-17

The following report is a data analysis of shooting incidents that occured in New York City’s boroughs. The data set gathered by the police department includes information pertaining to the time, date, location and demographics of both parties involved in each incident. You can reproduce the analysis by downloading the dataset “NYPD Shooting Incident Data (Hisoric)” from the www.data.gov website and following the code below.

df <- data %>%
  select("OCCUR_DATE", "OCCUR_TIME", "BORO", "LOC_OF_OCCUR_DESC", "PRECINCT", 
         "LOC_CLASSFCTN_DESC", "LOCATION_DESC", "PERP_AGE_GROUP", 
         "PERP_SEX", "PERP_RACE", "VIC_AGE_GROUP", "VIC_SEX", "VIC_RACE", "X_COORD_CD", "Y_COORD_CD","Latitude", "Longitude", "Lon_Lat" ) %>%
  mutate(
    BORO = as.factor(BORO),
    LOC_OF_OCCUR_DESC = as.factor(LOC_OF_OCCUR_DESC),
    PRECINCT = as.factor(PRECINCT),
    LOC_CLASSFCTN_DESC = as.factor(LOC_CLASSFCTN_DESC),
    LOCATION_DESC = as.factor(LOCATION_DESC),
    PERP_AGE_GROUP = as.factor(PERP_AGE_GROUP),
    PERP_SEX = as.factor(PERP_SEX),
    PERP_RACE = as.factor(PERP_RACE),
    VIC_AGE_GROUP = as.factor(VIC_AGE_GROUP),
    VIC_SEX = as.factor(VIC_SEX),
    VIC_RACE = as.factor(VIC_RACE)
  )

df <- df %>%
  add_count(BORO, name = "BORO_COUNT") %>%

  relocate(BORO_COUNT, .after = BORO)

The three graphs above raise several questions I’d like to explore further. In the first graph, Brooklyn had the highest number of shooting incidents from 2006 to 2022 and Staten Island had the fewest. This leads me to ask: what is the ratio of shootings to population in each borough and does individuals financial situation correlate to shootings?

The second graph highlights the monthly shooting trends in the Bronx, showing an increase in incidents during the summer months and a decrease in the winter months. This prompts me to wonder if the same pattern holds true across all New York City boroughs.

The third graph illustrates shooting incidents per month for all boroughs. However, it is not totally clear if the amount of shootings is significantly different for summer vs. winter months in all boroughs. Based on this visualization, it would be helpful to conduct more statistical analyses to determine if there is a significant difference in shooting incidents by season.

df$OCCUR_DATE <- as.Date(df$OCCUR_DATE, format = "%m/%d/%Y")

# Create a new month and season column for winter (December, January, February) and summer (June, July, August)
df <- df %>%
  mutate(MONTH = month(OCCUR_DATE),
         SEASON = case_when(
           MONTH %in% c(6, 7, 8) ~ "Summer",
           MONTH %in% c(12, 1, 2) ~ "Winter",
           TRUE ~ NA_character_))  
# Define the boroughs
boroughs <- c("BRONX", "BROOKLYN", "MANHATTAN", "QUEENS", "STATEN ISLAND")

# Initialize a data frame to store results
season_counts <- data.frame(BORO = character(), SEASON = character(), COUNT = integer(), stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

for (boro in boroughs) {

  summer_count <- df %>%
    filter(BORO == boro & SEASON == "Summer") %>%
    summarise(COUNT = n()) %>%
    mutate(BORO = boro, SEASON = "Summer")
  
  winter_count <- df %>%
    filter(BORO == boro & SEASON == "Winter") %>%
    summarise(COUNT = n()) %>%
    mutate(BORO = boro, SEASON = "Winter")
  
  if (nrow(summer_count) > 0) {
    season_counts <- bind_rows(season_counts, summer_count)
  }
  
  if (nrow(winter_count) > 0) {
    season_counts <- bind_rows(season_counts, winter_count)
  }
}
# View the results
print(season_counts)

The four heat maps appear to have more women than men perpetrators based on the width of the bars/colored area. However, after reviewing the two scales we can see that the opposite is true. This exemplifies the importance of choosing the best visualization tools to represent our data properly.

leaflet_map <- leaflet() %>%
  addTiles() %>%
  setView(lng = -74.0060, lat = 40.7128, zoom = 12) 

# Add points for female perpetrators
leaflet_map1 <- leaflet_map %>%

                   lat = ~Latitude,

                   radius = 3,

                   popup = ~paste("Incident Date:", OCCUR_DATE))

leaflet_map1
leaflet_map

The two plots above, where incidents overlay the map of the city best represents the difference in women and men perpetrators. The red and blue dots represent specific incidents and the exact longitude and latitude where they occured. This can better help people identify which streets in specific boroughs may be the most dangerous. If we did not map all of this information then it would be easy to assume or have a bias against Brooklyn as it had the greatest amount of total incidents.

Conclusion:

In this report I wrangled the data by first changing certain columns to factors. I then edited the time and date variables, so that they would be easier to interpret, and made a new column to represent the total amount of shooting incidents by borough.

The key things I wanted to determine was what borough had the most amount of shootings and which ones had the least amount.

I then wanted to determine if the month had any factor in the number of shootings that occurred. I first graphed the number of Brooklyn shootings by month, then used a comparative bar graph to show all of the boroughs next to each other.

Based off the comparative bar graph, it looked like there was more shootings in the summer months than in the winter months. To determine if there was a significant difference between shootings in the summer vs. winter for each borough I ran a two way anova as a statistical test. The Anova summary indicated that there was a significant difference between winter months (June, July and August) and summer months (December, January and February) for each borough.

At the end of my analysis I made four heat maps to compare the gender of the perpetrators in New York City. I then made two interactive maps so users can view exact locations and the date where shootings occurred. Had I not created the last two interactive maps it would appear that there were more women perpetrators than men, which is not the case. Furthermore, it would have gave a false bias on what areas have had the most shootings. For example, not every neighborhood in Brooklyn had high concentration of shootings. Some of the south west neighborhoods in Brooklyn had fewer shootings neighborhoods in Staten Island.

By using the interactive maps people can determine exact locations where the shooting occurred which will hopefully lead to more informed travel and living decisions.

I hope you enjoyed this data analysis on the NYPD shooting incident dataset.
